<DOC><DOCNO> AP880916-0086 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-09-16-88 0701EDT</FILEID><FIRST>r i PM-Peru     09-16 0349</FIRST><SECOND>PM-Peru,0360</SECOND><HEAD>Protesters Smash Store Windows In Protest Against AusterityMeasures</HEAD><HEAD>With PM-Peru-Inflation</HEAD><BYLINE>By MONTE HAYES</BYLINE><BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE><DATELINE>LIMA, Peru (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Demonstrators against government austeritymeasures smashed store windows with rocks, looted shops and clashedwith riot police. Officials said leftist guerrillas infiltrated thedowntown protest.   Thousands of pedestrians trying to escape the riots Thursday ranthrough streets filled with tear gas fired by police. Most wereunable to find shelter because stores and restaurants closed theirdoors when the violence started.   The government gave no report on the number of injured, but twoprotesters were seen bleeding from the head. Police made 30 arrests.   Small groups of demonstrators blocked traffic Thursday afternoonand shouted insults against harsh anti-inflation austerity measuresannounced last week by the center-left government of President AlanGarcia.   The measures included price increases of as much as 300 percentfor food staples and gasoline to eliminate costly governmentsubsidies that were contributing to inflation expected to top 900percent this year.   In addition to the protests against the steep price increases,about 300 striking civilian workers from a navy shipyard clashedwith police troopers who fired tear gas grenades to keep thestrikers from reaching the government palace.   Police said members of the Maoist-inspired Shining Pathguerrilla movement infiltrated the demonstrators and urged them onto violence. Men in hoods were seen among the protesters.   Police said the protesters smashed store windows and looted abook shop and a clothing store only two blocks from the governmentpalace.   Riot police regained control in the downtown area after severalhours.   In other violence Thursday, police said an assassination team ofMaoist rebels fired on a navy captain as he was driving his youngdaughter to school in an upper-class neighborhood, wounding himtwice in the stomach and twice in the left leg.   Police said the daughter, whose age was not available, was nothurt in the attack.   Four suspected members of the Shining Path armed with threerevolvers and sticks of dynamite were arrested as they tried toescape on foot, police said.</TEXT></DOC>